&gt;
No, it is possible because the scores are weighted. A bit more info... 

To obtain a fitness score a new player is tested against each player in 
the dominance chain. A test is currently just 2 games, one each way. 
Each of the games is scored as descibed by these constants:

        const double P1_SCORE_WIN = 2.0;
        const double P1_SCORE_DRAW = 1.0;
        const double P1_SCORE_LOSE = 0.0;

        const double P2_SCORE_WIN = 4.0;
        const double P2_SCORE_DRAW = 2.0;
        const double P2_SCORE_LOSE = 0.0;

So winning as player 2 is worth more than winning as player 1, etc. and 
each player being tested gets an overall score of between 0 and 6.0 (won 
both games). This score is then multiplied by the index of the dominance 
player on the chain (+1 &#39;cause the indexes are 0 based). This aproach 
wasn&#39;t scientifically arrived at, it just seemed like a good idea on the 
basis
that later player added to the chain are probably better than earlier ones.

Anyway, wehat this means is that a new player might be able to beat the 
current dominant player but not the whole chain, and therefore score 
more than the dominant player did.

